A simulation study based on Wilcoxon Signed Rank Test

Abhirup Sengupta, Subhasis Sur , Shantanu Nayek

2023-03-18

Introduction

  • Wilcoxon Signed Rank Test is a non parametric test for one sample location problem .

  • We assume that X1,X2,....,XnX1,X2,....,Xn is a iid sample from F(x)F(x) , where F belongs to a location family is continuous and symmetric about 0 and F(0) = 1/2

Now , we want to test the null hypothesis H0H0 against some alternative hypothesis

  • H1H1 : > 0
  • H2H2 : < 0
  • H3H3 : 0

Distribution free of the test statistic under H_0 for n = 10 :

  • Here we have taken the four distributions ( Normal , Cauchy , Laplace and logistic ) which satisfies the assumptions .

  • The test statistic is distribution free under H_0 for n = 10 .

Distribution free of the test statistic under H_0 for n = 20 :

  • The test statistic is distribution free under H_0 for n = 20 .

Distribution free under H_0 for n = 30 :

  • We repeat this process for n = 30 .

  • The test statistic is distribution free under H_0 for n = 30

Violation of Assumption ( Continuous assumption is violated) :

  • we draw the random sample from a discrete distributions namely, Poisson Distributions with parameter 2 .

  • Then we do the same process as before for sample sizes n = 10 .

  • from the plot , it is observed that both are not same .

  • taking n = 30

  • We do the same process as before for n = 30 .

  • from the plot , it is observed that both are not same .

Violation of Assumption ( Symmetricity assumption is violated) :

  • we draw the random sample from a non-symmetric distributions namely, Exponential Distributions with parameter 2 .

  • then We do the same process as before for sample sizes n = 10 .

- Both distributions are not same . This thing happens for violation of symmetry of F .

We do the same process taking random sample of sizes n = 30 from exponential distributions .

- Both distributions are not same . This thing happens for violation of symmetry of F .

Checking Wilcoxon Signed Rank Test can be written as the number of Walsh Averages

  • We draw a random sample of size n = 10 from cauchy distributions and find the values of Walsh Averages . We repeat this process upto 10,000 times .

Taking Sample sizes n = 20

  • We do the same process as before by taking random sample from Cauchy distributions for n = 20 .

Parametric Counterpart

  • Let us consider the case when a sample of size n is drawn from N(,^2), > 0 unknown
  • H0 : = 0 vs H1 : < 0 , unknown

  • Observation :

  • Considering the t-test , the power curve for the parametric test is converging faster to unity than that of the non-parametric setup for varying sample sizes.

  • Increase in sample size leads to faster rate of convergence to unity.

  • Both parametric and non-parametric setup shows that the tests are unbiased.

Parametric Counterpart

  • Let us consider the case when a sample of size n is drawn from Cauchy(,), > 0 unknown

  • H0 : = 0 vs H1 : 0 , unknown

  • Note : The samples are drawn from Cauchy population and t-test is used.

  • Observation :

  • Considering the z-test , the power curve for the non-parametric test is converging faster to unity than that of the parametric setup for varying sample sizes.

  • The possible reason for this scenario is the thicker tails for Cauchy Distribution.

Test statistic is taken to be Sample Median

  • Observation :

  • Considering the asymptotic distribution of median , the power curve for the parametric test is converging faster to unity than that of the non-parametric setup for varying sample sizes.

  • Both the scenarios show that the test is unbiased.
